AGI - The Regional Council of Sardinia, chaired by Alessandra Todde, approved a bill that provides an 18-month moratorium on energy production plants from renewable sources. Interventions for energy communities and photovoltaic systems on roofs are excluded. Meanwhile the Region counts that you arrive at the approval of the map of the suitable areas. The ddl, renamed 'Salva Sardegna', is likely to be challenged by the government once it is approved by the Regional Council. &nbsp;&nbsp;
<h2> What measures
The bill dictates a transitional discipline, for a maximum of 18 months, to guarantee the protection and safeguard of the landscape, of the landscape and environmental goods, anchored to the approval of the regional law on the identification of the suitable areas provided for in Article 20, paragraph 4 of Legislative Decree 8 November 2021, n. 199, and to the subsequent adaptation of the Regional Landscape Plan. "The urgency of this bill lies in the inderogable necessity, for the Sardinia Region, of being able to plan the use and consumption of the soil", reads in the report of the ddl, "in order to avoid the irreversibility of the potential damage deriving from the installation, construction, realization or start of new ones or other plants of production of electricity from renewable sources". The text of four articles does not affect the requests for authorization but stipulates the prohibition of creating new plants for the production of electricity from renewable sources > "subject to concession or authorization not yet granted or authorized, whether or not, at the time of approval of the bill, the authorisation or concession procedures are still underway". Electricity production plants are saved from renewable sources aimed at self-consumption.
&nbsp;
The ddl also provides that the Regional Council adopts the updating to the Regional Landscape Plan (Ppr) within 18 months of the date of entry into force of its approval and undertakes to adopt "all the initiatives provided for by the legislation in force to ensure and promote the celery approval of the decrees of the Minister of the Environment and Energy Security referred to in article 20, paragraph 1, of the Legislative Decree no. 199 of the same regional decree. Also within 18 months must be updated the Environmental Energy Plan of the Sardinia Region (Pears).
&nbsp;
<div </div
<em> The President of the Sardinian Region, Alessandra Todde, responds to the AGI on the stop to new production plants from renewable energy sources in Sardinia (video by Roberta Secci)</em>
<h2>Todde: "It is not a moratorium"
"It's not a moratorium. At this moment there are a far west and a normative void. We just took some time to say that we have to set up rules and negotiate with the state." The president of the Sardinia Region, Alessandra Todde, explains in a press point, the deliberation approved today in Giunta on the stop to the realization of new energy production plants from renewable sources in the island. "We simply said that, in the absence of rules, because the map of the suitable areas is missing, the revision and harmonization of the landscape plan with the internal areas, it is necessary to discuss these rules and we do not want to do so in the absence of a context that can tell to those who have to do the plants as they should do. So we asked for an 18-month suspensive, not so much about the authorizations as to the commissioning of the plants, because what is happening is an irreversible change."
&nbsp;
< blockquote
Todde hopes it'll take six months to make it clear. 18 for "cautelative" purposes have been indicated
</blockquote
&nbsp;
"There is no punitive intent on the ecological transition that - I remember - must take place. We still have two coal-fired power stations," said Todde, with reference to Enel's 'Deledda' power stations in Portovesme (South Sardinia) and Fiumensanto (Sassari). "The question is that we must decide on our territory, where to make plants, where to displace them and how these plants must be useful compared to the Regional Energy Plan. We have an annual consumption of 1.5 gigawatts; the Tyrrhenian Link transports 3 and we have demanded for more than 58 gigawatts, so the theme is really worrying. It is an unmeasured occupation. We therefore want to respect European standards, of course, and we want to put ourselves in the context in which these plants must serve industry and citizens." (We said that we want to bring back what is written in the Constitution, that the landscape is good and a value that is not negotiable," Todde argued. "It seems to me that it has been very negotiated lately; we want to place order on a void of which many have taken advantage, some legitimately others illegitimately." "We have inherited a situation of inertia because this situation of speculation has not been created in a month and has not been created in the last three months of electoral campaign," said the president of the Region, "but it has been created in the last 3-4 years, in which objectively the voice of the Region has never felt as well as the voice of many of those who today put themselves in the front row to scream speculation".
